                <p>Barley is now chiefly cultivated for malting, to prepare spirits and beer (see
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Brewing),</hi> but it is also largely employed in domestic
                    cookery. For the latter purpose the hard, somewhat flinty grains are preferable,
                    and they are prepared by grinding off the outer cuticle which forms “pot
                    barley.” When the attrition is carried farther, so that the grain is reduced to
                    small round pellets, it is termed “pearl barley.” Patent barley is either pot or
                    pearl barley reduced to flour. Under the name <hi rend="italic">decoctum
                    hordei,</hi> a preparation<pb break="no"
                    facs="ia:encyclopediabrit03newyrich/page/n392/mode/1up"
                    xml:id="kp-eb0903-0392-0377"/> of barley is included in the British
                    Pharmacopoeia, which is of value as a demulcent and emollient drink in febrile
                    and inflammatory disorders. For the cultivation of barley, see <hi
                    rend="smallcaps">Agriculture,</hi> vol. i. p. 358.</p>
